                            <div class="table-row">
                              <div class="table-cell"><%= item[0] %></div>
                              <div class="table-cell"><%= item[1] %></div>
                            </div>
                          <% }); %>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                      
                      

                    <h1>Detailed Instructions</h1>
                    <h2>SOFTWARE OBJECTIVE</h2>

                    <p>This annotation task aims for pin-pointing anatomical and appearance based landmark locations on animals. This will be done on video-material (extracted frames) or photos.</p>

                    <h2>SCOPE OF THE TAST</h2>
                    <p>If your submission is a video, usually not every frame needs to be annotated, quite often there are sequences where the interpolated positions between two key frames is still accurate enough.
                        A key frame is a frame in which you have manually annotated the animal landmarks. All other frames will either be empty or contained interpolated landmark positions (marked in grey). A frame will be turned into a key frame, once you manipulate it, e.g. by dragging on the interpolated nodes. (You´ll find an example for video-annotation below.)

                        If you work with photos (instead of a video), please, annotate all frames, not just one.
                    </p>

                    <h2>WORK FLOW</h2>
                    <p>
                        Possibly the best work-flow is to start annotating the first and the last frame of the given sequence. Then you should move the slider from either of these frames away to the other. Once a visible positional deviation is observable, correct the interpolated landmarks in that respective frame -- turning that frame into a key frame. Continue doing so until all frames are either manually pin-pointed or interpolated, correctly.
                    </p>

                    <h1>Hints:</h1>
                    <ul>
                        <li>The current landmark to be clicked is highlighted on the Navigator on the left-hand side</li>
                        <li>Always pin-point landmarks which are in the image, even if occluded (<span><shopicon-regular-show></shopicon-regular-show></span>)</li>
                        <li>Press the skip icon in the key point palette (<span><shopicon-regular-angledoubleleftsmall></shopicon-regular-angledoubleleftsmall></span>) when a key point is outside of image</li>
                        <li>You can also click on the landmark list</li>
                        <li>If landmarks are close to each other, click some place nearby and drag the landmark to its position</li>
                        <li>Start with first frame, then go to last frame. Whenever the interpolated positions in between deviate, correct the respective landmarks' positions</li>
                        <li>Sometimes a sequence may contain frames of multiple animals. Only annotate the animal in the foreground</li>
                        <li>If a landmark disappears or becomes invisible within consecutive frames, insert respective key frames to correct for this status</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>